<font color="#FF0000">COOK B. - MAD DOG MARINE</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jul 21 21:48:05 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook, Cook, man, you can certainly stir things up in the kitchen.  Communism is dead, except in your mind. It's over Cook. Capitalism won. The cold war is over. We don't need to keep calling each other by names long out of date.  Jane Fonda is long gone too, so is the Bay of Tonkin, except for old guys like you, who have to keep waving the flag, firing the gun, and shooting the war over and over and over until it becomes one big bore. Leave Jane alone, she is not an issue. Never was. Let Ted Turner and the exercise set enjoy her. She was always a Hollywood icon, never a real protestor. If she had any influence on the war, and comfort to the enemy, then it makes our soldiers look that much more simplistic and moronic.   That is not the legacy the men who died in Nam deserve. Or the civilians that were murdered by both sides. <br><br>
You can call me names, but you can't insult me. I proudly stood my ground and protested. I have no shame for that nor guilt. I was right, Cook, as much as it galls you, and history proves me right, the fact is that, pure and simple, that I was right and You Were Wrong. Sorry about that. You did you duty blindly, and you were wrong. Not wrong in being a good marine, just wrong in being sent to the wrong place by your so called leaders.  <br><br>
Look at the world today, Cook, take off your rosey-colored glasses. Those Nikes on your feet were made in Hanoi.  Your pants were made in slave labor camps in China. You can knock Clinton all you want (and I'll join you on most of that), but tell me Cook, what war duties exactly did Ronnie Reagon risk his Hollywood neck over?  Reagon was the biggest con job next to Viet Nam. JFK probably saw the trap that Nam was, and got his head blown off for wanting to stop it. The CIA had a field day, so did the military, and so what if they helped kill off a generation of American lads. <br><br>
I sleep good at night Cook, and have since the war, knowing that I following my heart, and my brain, and did what my patriotic soul knew was the right thing to do.  I did not need a .45 to prove I was a man, nor a 1-A draft card to tell me that I was &quot;wanted&quot;, and if I had to do it all over again, damn right I would be a protestor all over again.<br><br>
The bottom line Cook, is that we all were had. Those had the worst came home in bags. Next were the locals who got the treat of visiting Marines and Soldiers in THEIR COUNTRY, univited guests so to speak, and then come the rest of us. Loyal Americans to blinded by the flag to see the truth, Loyal Americans protesting a country gone mad with body counts, Loyal Americans who finally won the war by stopping it.  Hard to swallow isn't it Cook.  All that blood and sweat and tears, FOR NOTHING.  <br><br>
I guess Tom gave up trying to get through your tough hide, and now you have turned your sights onto me.  Take your best shot, Cook. I will still respect you, no matter how wrong you are, were, and continue to be.   Hey Cook, Peace and Flowers to you, Mad Dog Marine that you are.
<p><code>-- on file  (Doc Spatz) </code><p>


